photo.description: PROV. GERM. BIBL.SCRIPT. SOC.JESU [Stamp of the library of the German province of the Jesuit order. Probably to be read as "Provinciae Germaniae Bibliotheca Scriptorum Societatis Jesu" by analogy with the provenance inscription Provinciae Germaniae Bibliotheca Theologorum Societatis Jesu recorded here. CERL deals with the various permutations of German Jesuit provinces in the 20th and 21st centuries; possibly this stamp is to be dated prior to 1921, when the Niederdeutsche and Oberdeutsche Provinzen came into being (from a single Deutsche Provinz? the entry is unclear). Established heading: Jesuits. Deutsche Provinz] IHS DOM. COLON. [Stamp, with Jesuit emblems, of the Jesuit community in Cologne, Germany (founded 1544), struck through in pencil.] FÜRSTL. LEINING. HOF- BIBLIOTHEK [Stamp of the Fürstlich-Leiningische Bibliothek (or Fürstlich Leiningensche Bibliothek; the name appears to be spelled variously) at Amorbach, Germany. (Cf. another example in Wikimedia here.) After Abtei Amorbach was secularized, its buildings and library became the property of the recently created Prince of Leiningen, Carl Friedrich Wilhelm. The library remains a going concern today with some 31000 volumes, mostly concerned with family and local history, and looks gorgeous. DNB heading: Fürstlich-Leiningische Bibliothek] Penn Libraries call number: GC55 G9857 592v All images from this book

photo.description: Book label of John Penington & Son bookshop at 127 S. 7th Street in Philadelphia, PA. The Peningtons arrived in Pennsylvania in 1698 and were a leading and active Quaker family in Philadelphia business and politics. John Penington (1799-1867‏) and his son, Edward Penington, ran the book shop and specialized in rare and foreign books. John's father, Edward, was a bibliophile with a large personal library of over 6,000 volumes and was a prominent businessman in the city as a sugar refiner and merchant. Cf. the Penington Family Papers at the Historical Society of Pennsylvania. photo.description: Fürstlich Thurn und Taxische Hofbibliothek Regensburg Stamp of the Fürstlich Thurn und Taxissche Hofbibliothek in Regensburg, Germany. In origin the private library of Alexander Ferdinand, Fürst zu Thurn und Taxis (1704-1773), it was expanded by his son Carl Anselm (1733-1805) under the direction of Baron Franz Ludwig von Berberich. In 1812 the library moved with its owners into the former Reichstift St. Emmeram, a Benedictine monastery secularized in 1810, subsequently known as Schloss Thurn und Taxis. (The monastic library itself had previously been removed to Munich.) It is known today as the Fürst Thurn und Taxis Hofbibliothek und Zentralarchiv. Established heading: Fürstlich Thurn und Taxissche Hofbibliothek Penn Libraries call number: GC55 F4329 578n All images from this book

photo.description: INSIGNIA IACOBI REVTLINGERI VBERLINGEN : ANNO DOMINI 1582 Armorial stamp, dated 1582, of Jakob Reutlinger (1545-1611) of Überlingen, Germany. He held various offices in that city from 1576 on, eventually rising to Bürgermeister in 1600, in which position he served until his death from plague in 1611. He was a skilled diplomat and frequent traveler, often purchasing books for the Ratsbibliothek while abroad (the receipts are still held in the city archives; cf. Handbuch der historischen Buchbestände in Deutschland (Hildesheim: Ohms, 1992-2000), Bd. 9, p. 140). Reutlinger is best known for the "chronicle" of noteworthy events -- personal, social and political -- which he began writing in 1580; the manuscript had reached 16 volumes by the time he died. For biographical notes as well as a summary of Reutlinger's work, see R.W. Brednich, "Das Reutlingersche Sammelwerk im Stadtarchiv Überlingen als volkskundliche Quelle" in Jahrbuch für Volksliedforschung 10. Jahrg. (1965), p. 42-84. DNB heading: Reutlinger, Jakob, ‡d 1545-1611 Penn Libraries call number: GC55 Ei833 564c All images from this book
photo.title: Armorial stamp, dated 1582, of Jakob Reutlinger

photo.description: Honestate et pietate conspicuo, at[que] Amico Suo integerrimo Iacobo Reutlingero, Fr. Judoc[us] Schussler Franciscanus Pro[uinci]alis. Ex proprio, Dono Dedit 14. Marcij: Anno 15 . 82 16th-century ms. gift inscription, recording the presentation of this volume by Judocus [sic] Schüssler, a Franciscan provincial, to Jakob Reutlinger of Überlingen, Germany, near Lake Constance, on 14 March 1582. Schüssler is to be identified with Jodocus Schüssler, a Franciscan of Überlingen, who served as confessor to the Poor Clares of Bickenkloster zu Villingen; he was elected Provincial in 1565 but was removed in 1583, probably for a failure to perform required visitations (though he had previously been active in doing so). Cf. his entry in R. Henggeler and A. Bruckner, eds., Helvetia Sacra (Bern: Francke, 1972-), Abt. V, Bd. 1, p. 73.
